---
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import CaseStudySnapshot from "@/components/CaseStudySnapshot.astro"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"

const project = getProject("creative-printing-order-flow")!

const snapshotItems = [
  {
    label: "Problem",
    value:
      "Customers needed to move from job intent to the right order path faster.",
  },
  {
    label: "Primary users",
    value:
      "Local customers ordering print, signs, multimedia, or website services.",
  },
  {
    label: "Design move",
    value:
      "Put the main order categories directly on the homepage as large icon-grid entry points.",
  },
  {
    label: "Result",
    value:
      "Category grid shipped as the homepage entry point, reviewed with the shop owner, and still anchors the live site.",
  },
]
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="Creative Printing Order Flow"
  description="Redesigned the homepage order path around a responsive icon grid, helping customers choose the right print, sign, multimedia, website, or service intake route."
  seoTitle="Creative Printing Order Flow · UX Redesign"
  seoDescription="Redesigning Creative Printing’s homepage order path with responsive icon-grid navigation, clearer information architecture, and direct routes into service intake."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Creative Printing’s homepage needed to help customers start the right kind
    of order: copy and print, business cards, envelopes, wide format, signage,
    multimedia conversions, website work, or general service questions.
  </p>
  <p>
    I redesigned and built the order entry experience around a simple question:
    what are you trying to make? That moved the homepage from broad service
    browsing to a direct category grid.
  </p>

  <CaseStudySnapshot items={snapshotItems} />

  <h2>The Friction in the Flow</h2>
  <p>
    Customers often arrived with a specific job in mind, but print work spans
    different mental models. A business card order, a sign request, and a
    website refresh do not need the same questions or the same next step.
  </p>
  <p>I shaped the order path around three practical needs:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Different service types.</strong> Printing, signs, multimedia, and websites
      each needed a distinct entry point.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fast recognition.</strong> Customers needed to see their job type before
      reading through service pages.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mobile access.</strong> The order entry points had to be usable from
      small screens, not only from the desktop navigation.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Refactoring the Information Architecture</h2>
  <p>
    I restructured the homepage around the “Order Now” moment. Instead of making
    customers dig through navigation first, the page puts the main job
    categories in a large icon grid.
  </p>
  <p>
    The categories use plain service names customers already understand: “Copy &
    Print,” “Business Cards,” “Envelopes,” “Wide Format,” “Signage,” “Multimedia
    Conversions,” “Website Design and Hosting,” and “Questions About Services.”
    Each tile acts as a decision point, moving customers toward the relevant
    service page or intake form.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cleaning up the existing navigation would still have hidden the order
    categories one level down. The icon grid worked because the common job types
    were visible at once.
  </p>

  <div class="order-flow" aria-label="Creative Printing order flow">
    <div class="order-flow__node">
      <span>Homepage</span>
      <strong>Order Now</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="order-flow__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="order-flow__node order-flow__node--wide">
      <span>Category grid</span>
      <strong>Recognize the job type</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="order-flow__connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="order-flow__node">
      <span>Next step</span>
      <strong>Service page or intake form</strong>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Responsive Design and Implementation</h2>
  <p>
    I built the homepage and order grid to work across screen sizes, with large
    visual targets and clear labels. The interaction stayed simple: find the
    closest category, select it, and continue into the appropriate service path.
  </p>
  <p>
    The interface keeps the main service paths visible before customers commit
    to a form, so picking the wrong category costs one step back rather than a
    restart.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before launch, the shop owner reviewed the category grid and intake paths.
    That review kept the structure tied to how customers described their jobs,
    not only how the shop organized services internally.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    The redesigned order path shipped on Creative Printing’s homepage, giving
    customers a direct route from job type to intake form. Years later, the
    category grid still anchors the live site.
  </p>
  <p>
    This project was part of a broader engagement covering the shop’s full web
    presence and print production pipeline.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>

<style>
  .order-flow {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
  }

  .order-flow__node {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 0.375rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--background) 96%, var(--muted));
  }

  .order-flow__node span {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
    color: var(--muted-foreground);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .order-flow__node strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
  }

  .order-flow__connector {
    width: 1px;
    height: 1.25rem;
    margin-left: 1.25rem;
    background: var(--border);
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .order-flow {
      grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 2rem minmax(0, 1.2fr) 2rem minmax(
          0,
          1fr
        );
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0;
    }

    .order-flow__connector {
      width: 100%;
      height: 1px;
      margin-left: 0;
    }
  }
</style>
